{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01A7FqzztADehHAtBKfUxsyZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01F5EpkDMjqjK5WBHXEMjQp1","name":"StructuredOutput","input":{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"When a required key is absent from both the file and the environment, the error message names the missing key by its exact config path (e.g., `database.host`).","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"The failure is in error message generation logic, which is pure computation with no I/O. Mock the config dictionary to simulate a missing key, then verify the error message contains the exact path. Mocking won't hide this failure—if the code reports the wrong key name or omits it, the test catches it immediately.","test_description":"Mock the config loader to provide a config dict with a missing required key (e.g., no 'database.host'). Call the loader and catch the exception. Assert that the error message contains the exact path 'database.host' (not just 'host', not just 'database', and not omitted).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.85,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the environment variable `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` is set, the loader resolves the config file path relative to that directory rather than `~/.config`.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Path construction from environment variables is pure logic; no filesystem access needed to test it. Mock the environment variable and file I/O, then verify that the correct path is constructed and passed to the file reader. The real failure—code uses `~/.config` even when `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` is set—is caught by inspecting the path argument to the mocked file read.","test_description":"Set `XDG_CONFIG_HOME` to a test value in the environment. Mock the file read operation to capture the path argument. Call the loader and assert that the captured path is `{XDG_CONFIG_HOME}/tool/config.yaml`, not `~/.config/tool/config.yaml`.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.7,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.08,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When an environment variable with the `TOOL_` prefix conflicts with a key in the config file, the environment variable value is used.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Config merging is pure logic. Mock both file read (to return a config dict) and environment variables, then verify the final config object uses the environment variable value. Mocking won't hide the real failure—if the code uses the file value instead, the assertion fails immediately.","test_description":"Mock config file to return {'database': {'host': 'file-value'}}. Set environment variable `TOOL_DATABASE_HOST` to 'env-value'. Call the loader. Assert that the final config has database.host set to 'env-value', not 'file-value'.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When the config file contains a YAML syntax error, the error message includes the line number where the problem was detected.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"YAML parsing and error handling is pure computation—no I/O required. Pass a malformed YAML string directly to the parser (don't read from file), let it raise an exception, and verify the error message includes the line number. The YAML parser's error object (with problem_mark) is deterministic, so mocking isn't needed.","test_description":"Create a malformed YAML string with a syntax error on line 5 (e.g., missing colon in a key-value pair). Pass it to the config loader's YAML parser. Catch the exception and assert that the error message contains '5' or 'line 5'.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.75,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When the config directory does not exist at startup, the loader creates it and writes a defaults file before proceeding.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Filesystem operations are the real failure boundary. Mocking `mkdir` and file `write` would hide critical failures: wrong arguments to mkdir (e.g., missing `parents=True`), mkdir called after write instead of before, or write failing because the directory wasn't actually created. An Integration test using a real temporary directory catches these. The real failure—the directory doesn't actually exist after the loader runs—requires real filesystem operations to detect.","test_description":"Create a temporary directory path that doesn't exist. Call the config loader with that path. Verify the directory now exists (check with os.path.isdir). Verify a defaults file exists at the expected path (check with os.path.isfile). Optionally verify the file contains expected default content.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":10,"cache_creation_input_tokens":13346,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":13346},"output_tokens":4,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a07b227a-54ae-44d4-9fd5-91dcdd77fd70","uuid":"da8af7ff-ad56-4d09-a000-7e5f7e752d82"}
